irca 1078","1055":"1055","1053":"1053","1172":"1172","1082":"1082","nach 1147":"na 1147","Heimbach, Düren, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany":"Heimbach, Kreis Düren, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Duitsland","Heimbach, Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Allemagne":"Heimbach, Landkreis Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Duitsland","Heimbach, Düren, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Duitsland":"Heimbach, Kreis Düren, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Duitsland"},"en":{"um 1082–nach 1147":"about 1082–after 1147","1082–1147":"1082–1147","1091–1147":"1091–1147","1112–1172":"1112–1172","1055–1102":"1055–1102","1053–Female":"1053–Deceased","1091":"1091","um 1082":"about 1082","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","1112":"1112","UM 1078":"about 1078","1055":"1055","1053":"1053","1172":"1172","1082":"1082","nach 1147":"after 1147","Heimbach, Düren, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany":"Heimbach, Düren, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany","Heimbach, Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Allemagne":"Heimbach, Neuwied, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany","Heimbach, Düren, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Duitsland":"Heimbach, Düren, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hermann","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Jurgen, Mathias, Gottlieb, Horst, Juergen, Klaus, Lorenz, Bernd, Dieter, Erwin.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Hungary, Poland, Czechia, Slovakia, and some other European countries; see also below. Compare   Harman   5.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): adoption of German name (see 1 above). Compare   Herman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Heermann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Reinhard.","German: variant of   Hermann  ."]},{"name":"Armao","meanings":["Portuguese (<b>Armão</b>): adaptation of German   Hermann  .","Italian (Sicily; <b>Armào</b>): perhaps from a personal name related to ancient Germanic <i>Ermoald</i>. It could also be a variant of   Arnao  ."]},{"name":"Herl","meanings":["German: from a pet form of the personal name   Hermann  ."]},{"name":"Harman","meanings":["English (mainly southeast), Dutch, and Czech: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’ (see   Hermann  ). In England this name was introduced by the Normans.","Irish: variant of   Hargadon  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): perhaps a nickname for someone with a copious or noticeable head of hair (see   Haar  )."]},{"name":"Heer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernhard, Erwin, Hans, Alfons, Alois, Ewald, Kurt, Monika, Otto.","German and Dutch: from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name with the first element <i>hari</i>, <i>heri</i> ‘army’, as, for instance,   Hermann  . This surname is rare in the Netherlands.","Dutch: variant, without the definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’, of   De Heer  ."]},{"name":"Harms","meanings":["North German, Dutch, and Danish: patronymic from a short form of the personal name <i>Herman(n)</i> (see   Hermann  ).","English (London and southeastern England): variant of   Harm  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Harr","meanings":["North German: from a short form of any of the ancient Germanic personal names with the first element <i>hari</i>, <i>heri</i> ‘army’, for example,   Hermann  ,   Herbert  .","English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Hare  .","Norwegian (<b>Hårr</b>): habitational name from the farm name Hårr or Haarr south of Stavanger, of uncertain origin. In North America, this surname may also be an altered form of the variant <b>Haarr</b>."]},{"name":"Harmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Eldor.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’ (see   Hermann  )."]},{"name":"Armand","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Pierre, Lucien, Philippe, Serge, Alain, Andre, Andree, Camille, Etienne, Francoise, Gabrielle, Gardy.","French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian: from the French personal name <i>Armand</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hardman</i> or <i>Hariman</i>, composed of the elements <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’ or <i>hari</i> ‘army’ and <i>man</i> ‘man’ (see   Hermann  ). This surname is also found in England, where it is of Huguenot origin. Compare   Arman  ,   Arment  , and   Armond  .","History: This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Harmening","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Klaus, Otto.","North German: patronymic from a variant of the personal name   Hermann  ."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese: written 井伊 ‘well’ and ‘that’, the name one of Japan's great daimyō families, originally based in Tōtōmi (now part of Shizuoka prefecture), later in Kōzuke (now Gunma prefecture) and Ōmi (now Shiga prefecture). Other variants of the name substitute either character with similar sounding characters such as 飯 ‘cooked rice’, 居 ‘residence’, and so forth. It was formerly Romanized as <b>Iyi</b>. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Roman number <i>II</i> (meaning ‘the second’, i.e. ‘the younger’ of the two bearers of the name) is apparently also counted as a surname <i>Ii</i>.","History: Ii Naomasa (1561–1602) was awarded lands in Kōzuke and Ōmi for his service in the civil wars that won the shōgunate (military dictatorship) for Tokugawa Ieyasu. His family built the beautiful castle of Hikone, which still stands. His descendant Ii Naosuke (1815–1860) ruled Japan for two years as Tairō (Great Elder) and played a major part in signing treaties that opened Japan to foreign trade at the end of the Tokugawa Shōgunate. He was assassinated by adherents of the anti-foreign party."],"variants":[]},{"name":"von","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Ronald .  It is sometimes used as a given name in its own right."],"variants":[{"name":"Ronald","meanings":["From the Old Norse personal name <i>Rögnvaldr</i> (composed of <i>regin</i> ‘advice, decision’ (also, ‘the gods’) + <i>valdr</i> ‘ruler’). This name was regularly used in the Middle Ages in northern England and Scotland, where Scandinavian influence was strong. It is now widespread throughout the English-speaking world."]}]},{"name":"Heimbach","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: habitational name from any of numerous places called Heimbach."],"variants":[{"name":"Himebaugh","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Heimbach  ."]},{"name":"Heimbaugh","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Heimbach  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hermann II von Heimbach was born about 1082, in Heimbach, Neuwied, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany, his father, Hermann Ier von Heimbach von Hengebach, was 28 and his mother, Judith von Malsen von Sponheim, was 31. He had at least 1 son with Petrissa van Saffenberg. He died after 1147, in his hometown."},"et":{"um 1082–nach 1147":"umbes 1082–pärast 1147","1082–1147":"1082–1147","1091–1147":"1091–1147","1112–1172":"1112–1172","1055–1102":"1055–1102","1053–Female":"1053–Surnud","1091":"1091","um 1082":"umbes 1082","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","1112":"1112","UM 1078":"umbes 1078","1055":"1055","1053":"1053","1172":"1172","1082":"1082","nach 1147":"pärast 1147","Heimbach, Düren, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany":"Heimbach, Kreis Düren, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Saksamaa","Heimbach, Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Allemagne":"Heimbach, Landkreis Neuwied, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksamaa","Heimbach, Düren, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Duitsland":"Heimbach, 